The picture below shows a vector 
                     \Vect{s}
                   in 
                     \RNr[2]
                  , together with its orthogonal complement 
                     \Vect{s}^{\bot}
                  , the line perpendicular to 
                     \Vect{s}
                  . (The red dot represents the origin.)

Note that 
                     \Vect{s}^{\bot}
                   consists of an infinite collection of vectors, namely all those vectors which are perpendicular to 
                     \Vect{s}

The orthogonal complement of the set 
                     S:=\Set{ \Vect{s},\Vect{t} }
                   consists of all vectors in the plane which are perpendicular to both 
                     \Vect{s}
                   and 
                     \Vect{t}
                  . Thus the orthogonal complement of 
                     S
                   is the intersection of the hyperspace perpendicular to 
                     \Vect{s}
                   and the hyperspace perpendicular to 
                     \Vect{t}
                  . In this case 
                     S^{\bot}
                   is just the origin, represented here by a red dot.
